{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629651"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:08:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:08:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17294"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17294"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.03,0.69,0.08,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69738"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9984"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"126"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7231"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23384"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23391"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69738"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after a fall from a ladder. He reports difficulty moving his right arm. Neurological examination reveals loss of extension at the shoulder, elbow, wrist, and fingers on the right side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely to have been injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary","Musculocutaneous","Radial","Median","Ulnar"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of loss of extension at the shoulder, elbow, wrist, and fingers is indicative of an injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. The radial nerve innervates the muscles responsible for extension in these areas, and its injury can lead to a condition known as wrist drop, where the patient is unable to extend the wrist and fingers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles, affecting shoulder abduction rather than extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the anterior compartment of the arm, primarily affecting flexion at the elbow rather than extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for innervating the anterior forearm and some intrinsic hand muscles, primarily affecting flexion and pronation rather than extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the intrinsic muscles of the hand and some forearm muscles, affecting fine motor control and grip strength rather than extension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The radial nerve is responsible for extension at the shoulder, elbow, wrist, and fingers.","Injury to the radial nerve can result in wrist drop and loss of extension in the upper limb.","Understanding the function of different peripheral nerves is crucial for diagnosing nerve injuries."],"references":["Polcaro L, Charlick M, Daly DT. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Brachial Plexus. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531473/","Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55192"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17294"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55192"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T15:46:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T15:46:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9984"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69738"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":